I see in the structure definition that the fields on an smbios_version_t are of type uint8_t, while the arguments to this function are uint_t. Is it a problem (correctness- or readability- wise) to compare these two types of values without a cast?

That's a good question. In terms of correctness, as both are unsigned, it's generally fine. In C, there is a type promotion that is applied such that a smaller type is promoted to a larger type. In general, assignments and when signedness differs, are the major places where one has to be careful of this.
OOC, is there a reason we wouldn't want something like this in libjedec? Namely, a function to convert an id to the correct bank and identification code?

In general, when dealing with outputting something that's not in any particular state, I try to avoid putting that into a shared library. In this case, the way we're printing it is very specific to how the smbios command wants to use it. Here we're using a FILE *. Someone else may want to output by using snprintf/asprintf to a shared buffer and going from there. Basically, this feels very specific to the consumer.

For example, the idea of the description string in the function is very smbios specific. If we had another program that wanted to use this library, it's not clear to me that it would want to use the same output.

Now, another thing to ask is should we have an interface that takes apart the combined id automatically. I opted not to initially because that again felt specific to SMBIOS versus the actual construction of the library. It's also not 100% clear to me how its represented in the DIMM SPD data that this is derived from.

Does that make some sense?

I think I'm missing something obvious: Why wouldn't this expression always be true?

I'm not sure it's obvious. There are two major entry points defined in the SMBIOS specification. The 32-bit one was defined in SMBIOS 2.x and the 64-bit one was defined in SMBIOS 3.0. Now, just because they were defined in that version doesn't mean that they actually happen to have that version. In SMBIOS 3.2 they issued an update that says they're supposed to be the same version. However, in the field we've found that not to be true.

The issue we encountered here was that the 32-bit version has an older version than the 64-bit entry point. However, there's no reason the reverse can't be true.

Since there's nothing that actually guarantees this, I believe we have to check.

OOC, how did you find which value definitions needed to be added -- e.g., SMB_PRU_* and other #define values added to this file? For the structure definitions, I see the SMBIOS spec marks which versions can be expected to have various fields. Sampling a few of the new values for these fields, though, I do not see the 3.2 spec clearly mark them as added in 3.2., though if I look at the previous version of the spec, that is clearly true. I'm wondering if there is a simpler way to know which values have been added between versions. (I am looking at PDF versions of the spec -- I would guess there is a non-PDF form that might be easier to diff somehow, but I am curious!)

I did this in two different ways. The first is that I used the Annex C informative change log.

The second is that I went and then for different sections just pulled up older versions of the PDF and compared the allocated numbers. Basically I just did it the max power way, aka brute forcing it with my eyes and hoping I don't miss things.
Hah, okay. Thanks for explaining. Sounds like my intuition that the max power way might be needed wasn't too far off!

This might be a dumb question, but: Why is the "smblp" prefix used for fields in the smbios_slot_peer_t struct, as opposed to "smbsp" ("SMBIOS slot peer")? My guess is that it's because the smbios_slot_t uses the "smbl" prefix for its struct fields, but it's not clear to me what the "l" stands for there.

The way I derived this was based on the base type, the smbios_slot_t. It uses prefix of smbl to stand for smbios_slot. This was probably originally done because smbios_system_t has smbs. Because this is really used in my mind as a follow on to the already existing smbios_slot, I just added a p to make it the peer.

I'll admit, this is pretty arbitrary.
